# 🖥️ Wazuh SIEM Deployment - Phase 2: System Auditing & Endpoint Monitoring

This phase documents the expansion of the monitoring perimeter to a remote Windows host. It covers the deployment of the Wazuh Agent infrastructure, local architectural logging via Microsoft Sysmon, and the integration of a security-hardening configuration matrix to pipeline telemetry back to the central manager `buffer`.

## 🏗️ Endpoint Topology
* **Target OS:** Windows 10/11 x86_64
* **Endpoint Hostname:** `window`
* **Network Infrastructure:** Routed via dedicated Wi-Fi adapter network bridge to host VM.

---

## 🚀 Deployment Steps & Execution

### 1. Wazuh Agent Infrastructure Provisioning
The Wazuh agent was deployed on the remote Windows endpoint using an elevated PowerShell instance to fetch the official package and register the endpoint silently against the manager IP.

```powershell
# Executed via Administrator PowerShell to pull package and link manager
Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "[https://packages.wazuh.com/4.x/windows/wazuh-agent-4.14.5-1.msi](https://packages.wazuh.com/4.x/windows/wazuh-agent-4.14.5-1.msi)" -OutFile "$env:tmp\wazuh-agent.msi"; msiexec.exe /i "$env:tmp\wazuh-agent.msi" /q WAZUH_MANAGER="192.168.18.157" WAZUH_AGENT_NAME="window"

# Initialize local endpoint host service
Start-Service -Name "Wazuh"

# Navigate to deployment matrix workspace
cd "$env:USERPROFILE\Downloads\Sysmon"

# Install background service mapped to security configuration
.\Sysmon64.exe -i sysmonconfig.xml

<!-- File Location: C:\Program Files (x86)\ossec-agent\ossec.conf -->
<localfile>
  <location>Microsoft-Windows-Sysmon/Operational</location>
  <log_format>eventchannel</log_format>
</localfile>

# Apply configuration modifications by restarting the target agent
Restart-Service -Name "Wazuh"

